  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concern—it's a real, tangible issue that affects real people who are trying to do their best. As a carpenter with a vocational diploma and a dad of three, I've seen firsthand how people's confidence can be eroded by the idea that they don't belong in certain fields. When someone grows up thinking they're 'not smart enough' for engineering or physics, that belief can become a self-fulfilling prophecy. I've heard from students in my community who avoid STEM courses because they worry about being labeled as 'not cut out for it.' But stereotype threat isn't about innate ability—it's about the psychological burden of being perceived as part of a group that's historically underrepresented in these fields. It's especially harmful for people of color and women, who often face implicit biases that make them question their own skills. Addressing it requires more than just awareness; it needs concrete actions like mentorship programs that pair students with role models who look like them, and inclusive classroom environments where everyone feels valued. For example, in Philadelphia, where I live, some community centers have started workshops that focus on problem-solving in a way that's accessible to all, without the pressure of 'being good at math.' The key is to create spaces where people feel safe to make mistakes and learn without fear of judgment. If we want to build a future where everyone has a chance to contribute to STEM, we must tackle this issue head-on—not by trying to change people's minds, but by changing the systems that make them feel like they don't belong.",
